                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d607">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">701.2123/18: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dearing</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-02-20T13:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 20, 1933—1 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>36. Your 90, February 19, 11 a.m., and 91, February 19, midnight. Department has
                    noted that the Peruvian Government has given every assurance of prompt and
                    adequate protection, and promises an investigation and report of the attack on
                    the Colombian Legation and punishment of those found to be guilty. In view of
                    this, and as it does not appear from your reports that American lives are at
                    present in any actual danger, the Department, as at present advised, believes
                    that the despatch of a war vessel to Peruvian waters would not be warranted.
                    Please follow situation closely and keep Department promptly advised of
                    developments. It is assumed that you are in touch with American consular agents
                    in Peru as to the safety of Americans.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
